@MrSmackdab Close but no bananas. (You&#39;re wrong).
It is Newtonian physics in action, but for a second unconnected ball to hit the ground at the same time, it would have to be dropped from the same height as the centre of mass of the slinky/ball system, not next to the top.
The entire slinky, with or without the ball, falls with an acceleration of g (9.8ms2). It&#39;s just that as the top end is accelerating more rapidly, the it cancels the acceleration on the lower end.
